Conditionals and loops.

Now we give scripts the ability to make decisions and to repeat work. Start with the if-statement. Here's the crucial insight: in the shell, if runs on a command's exit code. An exit code of zero means true, or success, and any non-zero code means false. And the condition can be any command at all. So you can write if, then a bracket-bracket test, then semicolon then. You chain alternatives with elif, and a final else.

The condition itself usually uses the test command, which has three equivalent forms: the word test, single square brackets, and double square brackets. In bash, prefer the double-bracket form; it behaves the same but adds niceties like logical and-and and or-or, regular-expression matching, and it doesn't force you to quote your variables. The operators worth memorizing come in three groups. For files: dash-e for exists, dash-f for a regular file, dash-d for a directory, and dash-r, dash-w, dash-x for readable, writable, executable. For strings: dash-z for empty, dash-n for not empty, equals and bang-equals for comparison, and equals-tilde for a regex match. And for numbers, the funny two-letter ones: dash-e-q, dash-n-e, dash-l-t, dash-g-t, and so on. You can combine conditions with and-and, or-or, and bang inside double brackets, or use short-circuits, like bracket-bracket dash-d slash-backup bracket-bracket or-or mkdir slash-backup, meaning "make the directory only if it doesn't already exist." And when you have many alternatives, the case statement is cleaner than a long elif chain; its patterns are globs, and you end each branch with a double semicolon.

Then, loops, in three shapes. A for-loop iterates over a list, a glob, or a range, like for i in brace-one-dot-dot-five. A while-loop runs as long as a condition holds true. And an until-loop runs until a condition becomes true, which is perfect for "wait for this service to come up."

And here is the single most important pattern in this section, the correct way to read a file line by line: while, I-F-S-equals, read dash-r line, do, dot dot dot, done, with the file redirected in. Memorize that exact form. The I-F-S-equals preserves leading and trailing whitespace, and the dash-r stops backslashes from being mangled. Finally, inside any loop, break exits the loop entirely, and continue skips ahead to the next iteration.
